        "text": "<@UJBAJNFLK> thinking about your last link some more, I think I see a gap in its argument.\n&gt; • Web 2.0 — *User-generated content, host-generated authority*. ..a lot more user-generated, interactive content, but these sites have grown to become powerful platforms, and the fact that users don’t ultimately have control over their accounts and content is becoming problematic.\n&gt; • Web 3.0 — *User-generated content, user-generated authority*. ..Servers can choose whether or not to host someone’s account or content, but they don’t have ultimate authority over it.\nThis analysis glosses over the thorny question of behavioral data. A lot of the power of major platforms comes from behavioral data rather than user-generated content.",
